FSMs (extremely common)

Design a traffic light FSM (Moore vs Mealy, state encoding)
Design a sequence detector (e.g. detect "1011", overlapping and non-overlapping)
Design a vending machine FSM

FIFOs (asked almost everywhere)

Write a synchronous FIFO with full/empty flags
Write an asynchronous FIFO with Gray-coded pointers — this is one of the most broadly tested structures and forms the basis for several types of problems Thedatabus
Calculate minimum FIFO depth given producer/consumer rates

Arbiters and flow control

Design a fixed-priority arbiter
Design a round-robin arbiter Glassdoor
Implement valid/ready handshaking (backpressure) — backpressure is asked often; know the valid-ready protocol and alternatives like valid-credit Chipinsights

Counters and shift registers

Design a parameterized N-bit counter with synchronous reset
Design a shift register (SIPO, PISO, PIPO variants)
Design a clock divider (divide by N)

Basic combinational blocks

(FINISHED) - Write an N-bit adder / carry lookahead adder
Design a parameterized mux tree
Build an XOR gate using only NAND gates (gate-level structural RTL) Thedatabus

Timing and pipeline

Add pipeline registers to a given combinational path to meet timing
Design a simple 2-stage pipeline with stall/flush logic

Memory interfaces

Design a register file (synchronous read or async read variants)
Implement a basic AXI-lite slave interface — asked whenever you have any AXI experience on your resume Chipinsights

Architecture level

Describe and implement the steps to go from RTL to FPGA bitstream — often asked as a coding + explanation hybrid GitHub


The ones you should prioritize given your background are the async FIFO, round-robin arbiter, sequence detector, and AXI-lite slave — those four come up constantly and your RISC-V/FPGA project gives you natural context to tie them to.
